Comments: Limbs screwed off trees, express train sound. Tornado at Topar (E of Broken Hill) and possibly at Eldee (NW of Broken Hill) damaged trees and a garden shed.

Information passed on from Mike Bergen who spoke to the man who witnessed the funnel cloud while travelling on a bus to Wagga. The cell was about 15-20 km south of the coach. The cell was large, solitary and funnel cloud was distinct. The tornado was not observed to have touched-down". Tornado seen from bus by ex met observer on route to Wagga"

VERY NARROW AND TALL, FAIRLY STRAIGHT FROM GROUND TO CLOUD LEVEL. OBSERVED HALFWAY BETWEEN MACQUARIE CENTRE AND BLUE MTS.  NO DAMAGE OBSERVED. ON SYDNEY HARBOUR AROUND SAME TIME TWO WATERSPOUTS WERE OBSERVED NEAT ROSE BAY. Severe thunderstorms caused  $20 million damage in Sydney metro area.  3 cm hail and damaging winds were reported. A possible tornado sighting between Kellyville and Chatswood, and waterspouts were observed on Sydney Harbour.

400 to 500 kg tree completely stripped and thrown 150 m. Sheds completely demolished, cars and a bus pushed off the road, the bus was rolled over. A sheep was thrown 1 km. Wild-life killed. A 2 ton cattle feeder was thrown 300 yards uphill.  The funnel cloud was black in colour. Tornado reported at 0430 UTC on 25/11/94 10 to 15 km east of Condobolin.
Cobar hit with tornado and large hail.

O'Brien calls it a 'willy willy'. Steve Malley from Canberra Met Office obseved the tornado also. O'Brien writes "a band of uintense but brief rain and wind squalls crossed the region...at about 2145 [LT] rain and strong gusty E to SE developed to 60 km/hr. By 2000 [LT] the wind veered rapidly through 180 degrees with equally strong W/NW winds." Tornado in Canberra 28th January 1995
4.2 cm hail near Kangaloon at 0545 utc on 15/12/95.
No damage reported. Tornado sighting about 20 km east of Moree at 0150 UTC 0n 20/11/95.  No damage reported.
TRACTORS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN, ROOFS OFF SHEDS AND HOMES. Wind gusts and 4.2 cm hail at Coolamon. A tornado and 4.2 cm hail 5 km south of Rosewood at around 0500 UTC on 30/11/95.
Tornado at Bearbung near Gilgandra at 0330UTC on 29/9/96. Destroyed trees and fences, moved cars 200m, moved a full silo off foundations, unroofed a house.

Ironbark trees 600mm dia broken and pulled out of ground, destroyed a house and several sheds. Extensive damage to fences, moved a 4 tonne truck several lengths. Loud roaring noise heard as well as a deep humming sound. Tornado with 4 cm hail at Elong Elong at 0330 UTC on 29/9/1996. Tornado also reported from Bearbung near Gilgandra and 4 cm hail was reported from Eumungerie.
Woolshed and other buildings damaged. Trees felled. Tornado at Bundella at 0600 UTC on 29/9/1996.

39 caravans overturned or damaged at local caravan park (6 destroyed), 26 units damaged in retirement village, 11 homes suffered roof damage. Tornado (F1) with gusts to 65 kt reported from Fingal Bay at 1800 UTC on  30/6/1998.

One large 4wd rolled over another car ended up ontop of another. A weatherboard house was severely damaged. A baby was sucked out of the house but fortunately was uninjured. Tornado ranked F2 reported from Swinging Ridges Rd (12 km SW of Willow Tree) at 0930 UTC on 27/7/1998.

3 tornado tracks were observed during damage survey. A tornadic thunderstorm moved through the Sydney Metropolitan Area over the afternoon/early evening of 3/11/2000. Around 300 jobs were attended to by SES

Several homes lost roofs, whole (large) trees uprooted and other very localised damage reported. Tornado as well as 6cm hail reported from Uki (E side of Mt Warning) at 0625 UTC on 5/11/2000. Another tornado earlier at Nimbin at 0540 UTC on 5/11/2000.

40 foot palms thrown, goods blown out of house. Accompanied by shriek, 4-6cm hail and toad fall. Narrow swathe. Tornado as well as 6cm hail reported from Uki (E side of Mt Warning) at 0625 UTC on 5/11/2000. Another tornado earlier at Nimbin at 0540 UTC on 5/11/2000.
Time uncertain - inferred from radar. Tornado (F0) at Careel Bay (near Avalon) at about 0235UTC on 18/11/2001.
Tornado lifted garden shed at Leppington (Sydney) at 0500UTC on 18/11/2001.
Tornado overturned moored yachts at Cronulla at 0515UTC on 18/11/2001.
Tornado seen by spotter just west of Moree at 0915UTC on 02/02/2002.

Tornado 100 metres wide lifted hayshed, sucked water from river and uprooted trees 1.5 metres (5 feet) in diameter. On the 7/2/02 at 4:00UTC, near Ebor an 100m wide tornado was spotted travelling in an Easterly direction.  Uprooted large trees, hayshed and water from Serpentine River. Comments: Jimmy Deguara reported a tornado on the ground with debris swirl. The tornado was stationary and growing larger into a large cone. Debris hit a substation. The event was captured on film. A left moving supercell moved NE through the Northen Rivers towards Lismore during the afternoon. The cell weakened slightly as it came into Lismore city, but just as it was past Lismore it interacted with some weaker cells moving towards the SW with the general flow. This generated a tornado that impacted on the town of Dunoon. The SES received 116 RFA's for this event, damage was initially estimated to be in excess of $2 million, and the area was declared a natural disaster zone.

Camera and video footage of tornado showing tornado attached to convective cell. Tornado developed on convergence line associated with intense convective cell. No meso-cyclone was evident on radar - likely to be boundary layer instigated. 14 May 2007 15:00 local LARA: Tornado
3/12/07: Flash flooding from severe thunderstorms occurred in Boronia, Diamond Creek, Montrose, Leongatha, Eltham from same cell complex. Tree damage near Loch consistent with that from a tornado.
Detail unknown 20/12/07 Stockyard Hill tornado sighting detail sketchy.
Video footage fom Clyve Herbet although path length etc unknown 20/12/07 Skipton Confirmed tornado sightings.

Broad colum block of wind with low balck cloud associated, inless than 100m strip. Stripped tress and fences, picked up hay bales and ripped door off machinery shed. 20 tiles off roof of a house. 21/12/07: Elmore - possible tornado sighting, broad column of wind from low dark cloud
13 people suffered injury as a result of the tornado. 22-11-1968.
Possible tornado near Texas around 2:40pm AEST. Some damage reported, though no specific details noted. 29-10-1970.

Possible tornado near Kin Kin around 9:30pm AEST. Reports of 25 buildings damaged, though no images or specifics around the damage available. 3 deaths were attributed to the event. Hail to about 4cm in size was also reported. 14-08-1971.
No additional notes or images around the event. 07-11-1971.
No additional notes or images around the event. 28-11-1971.
No additional notes or images around the event. 09-11-1972.

Tornado observed between Brookfield and Eight Miles Plains. Reports of 500 houses unroofed, 1390 houses damaged and 500 declared structually unsafe. Media images showed a home blown off its foundations, roofs and walls torn off numerous homes. 04-11-1973.
Possible tornado near Toowoomba around 4:15pm AEST. Eight buildings were damaged during the event, though no images or specific details on the damage available. 04-12-1976.
Possible tornado at Torrens Creek around 5:45pm AEST. Seven buildings were damaged during the event, though no images or specific details on the damage available. 07-12-1976.
Possible tornado at Margate around 3pm AEST. Reports of at least 70 buildings damaged during the event, though no images or specific details on the damage available. 21.02-1977.

Possible tornado at Gayndah around 6pm AEST. Reports of ten buildings damaged (three demolished), though no images or specific details on the damage available. A heavy metal cattle feeder found more than a kilometre away on a neighbouring property. 01-12-1978.
Possible tornado at Benowa around 9:30am AEST. Reports of stables unroofed. 14-12-1978.

No additional comments or images around this event. 15-12-1980. Widespread thunderstorms in Southeast District late in afternoon with heavy rain and hail reported. Church damaged at Warra at 0730 utc. Nine house suffered roof damage at Ipswich. Report of hail " 3/4 the size of tennis balls " from Thornton. Power blackouts in Brisbane metropolitan area. (C Kotterer Diary)

Possible tornado at Mungar around 3:40pm AEST. Reports of at least five injuries,fifteen houses damaged between Maryborough and Point Vernon (some partly unroofed) and seven huts either blown down or damaged during the thunderstorm event. 01-06-1981. Thunderstorm reported in the Maryborough area in late afternoon, property damage from strong winds reported from Mungar Junction ; 3 homes and 7 huts either blown down or damaged. Three homes partly unroofed at Pt Vernon. Thunderstorm reported from Pt Curtis, with strong winds and hail causing property damage.          (C Kotterer Diary)

Tornado observed at Coolum around 5pm AEST. Reports of property damage between Caloundra and Noosa (estimated at $1 million), though it is unclear what portion of this damage was related to the tornado. 13-11-1981. Widespread thunderstorms over southeast Qld with hail and strong winds. Property damage between Caloundra and Noosa estimated at $1 million. Thunderstorms reported at Warwick 0015 utc, at Brisbane 0115 and 0400 utc, at Archerfield 0315 utc, at Oakey from 0300 utc, at Coolangatta 0545 utc. (C Kotterer Diary)

Tornado observed at Mudgeeraba around 6am AEST. Reports of two buildings damaged, though no pictures or specific details of the damage available. Heavy rain also occurred, which lead to localised flooding. 19-03-1983. Severe thunderstorm event listed in John Butler's Database.

Possible tornado at Cotton Tree Beach around 1:30am AEST. Reports of one death and seven injured. Reports of extensive damage at the Cotton Tree Caravan Park at Maroochydore, including thirteen caravans destroyed and trees blown over. One caravan was reportedly lifted up and tossed 20 metres onto its roof and another five metre caravan was tossed nearly 200m. NULL

Tornadoes observed ober Moreton Bay around 3pm AEST. One tornado alledgedley came ashore and caused property damage in Redcliffe and Margate, including two houses unroofed, twenty other houses damaged and a trawler sunk at Redcliffe. NULL

Tornado sighted at Daisy Hill around 4pm AEST. Reports of  extensive property damage between Ipswich and the southern suburbs of Brisbane, including 1000 houses damaged, some damage to caravans, trees blown over and power blackouts. One caravan alledgedly flew 5m across a road and landed on the caravan of a neighbour. Damage estimated at $5 million. Large hail reported. NULL
Possible tornado at Emu Park (exact time of the event is unknown). Reports of damage to five buildings, though no images or specific details on the damage available. NULL

Tornado observed in Redcliffe around 1pm AEST. Reports of a large amount of damage at Clontarf and near the Redcliffe Aero Club. Damage bill of approximately $10 million. Two deaths were associated with the thunderstorm, including one that drowned as the boat she was in overturned and the other touched a live fallen wire. A yacht at Newport Marina recorded winds of 100 knots before failing. During the event there were 500 homes unroofed, 1000 damaged and 12 strucurally unsafe. Light planes at Redcliffe Airport were flipped over. There were images of corrugated iron almost two-thirds of the way thorugh a palm tree at Clontarf. 24-12-1989. Severe Thunderstorm developed to the south of Warwick and moved NNE up the coast and through Brisbane and the northern bayside suburbs.  Damage in its path between Ipswich and Redcliffe, with the worst affected area being Redcliffe where it is believed a tornado contributed to $10 million worth of damage.  The thunderstorm claimed two deaths.  One drowned as the boat she was in overturned, the other touched a live fallen wire.

Possible tornado at Oakhurst around 2:40pm AEST. Reports of a discontinuous path of destruction through sparsely populated country with one brick house completely destroyed and several others suffered roof damage.  Windows were smashed by hail up to golf ball in size. Three cattle were destroyed after sustaining injury from flying debris.  Large area of pine plantation flattened.Tornado left a discontinuous path of destruction through sparsely populated country. One brick house was completely destroyed. Three cattle were destroyed after sustaining injury from flying debris. Large area of pine plantation flattened. 29-11-1992. Severe thundersorm day across southeast Queensland. A cell developed to the southwest of Maryborough during the early afternoon. The cell then split with a left mover and right mover resulting. The right mover is not reported to have produced any damage. However the left mover moved northeast towards Maryborough, generated a tornado in the unpopulated area of Oakhurst, leaving a discontinuous path of destruction in its wake. One brick house was completely destroyed and several others suffered roof damage. Windows were smashed by hail up to golf ball in size. 3 cattle had to be destroyed due to injury sustained by flying debris. Hundred of acres of pine forest were flattened in the wake of the tornado. 29-11-1992. Severe thundersorm day across southeast Queensland. The right mover is not reported to have produced any damage. Windows were smashed by hail up to golf ball in size.  3 cattle had to be destroyed due to injury sustained by flying debris.  Hundred of acres of pine forest were flattened in the wake of the tornado.

Tornado observed in the Bucca and Kolan area around 3:30pm AEST. Reports of extensive property and flora damage, including nine houses that were extensively damaged or destroyed. 20 cattle were killed or had to be destroyed. An eyewitness account noted stones embedded in trees, 16-20cm saplings approximately 4-5m long driven through 5 walls of houses, picture fram embedded in opposite wall, fridge missing weeks later and 3 tonne truck body blown or carried 300 metres. 29-11-1992. Widespread severe thunderstorm activity over southeast Queensland.  Severe thunderstorm through Bucca with associated tornado. Caused extensive wind and hail damage.

Possible tornado in parts of Hervey Bay around 1am AEST. Reports of several buildings and caravans damaged during the event. The Pialba caravan park was heavily impacted with two caravans tipped on their side and an annex alledgedly ripped to shreds. 5 people from the caravan park were taken to hospital. Extensive damage sustained to some homes and businesses in Point Vernon and Scarness, including the collapse of a 30 x 5 metre section of brick side wall of a boys department store in Main Street and numerous reports of partial roof loss. No images of the damage were available for assessment and therefore confidence in the assigned Fujita number is not high (could be greater). 21-01-1995. AT APROXIMATELY 1AM ON THE MORNING OF 21 JANUARY 1995 AN EVENT DESCRIBED LOCALLY AS A MINI CYCLONE CAUSED STRUCTURAL AND TREE DAMAGE IN THE VICINITY OF THE PIALBA CARAVAN PARK.  THIS EVENT DOES NOT SEEM TO BE A SEVERE THUNDERSTORM AND NO DEFINITE CAUSE CAN BE DEDUCED FROM THE EYEWITNESS OR DAMAGE DESCRITIONS. ONE POSSIBILITY IS DAMAGE FROM A LANDFALLING WATERSPOUT WHILE ANOTHER IS THE PRESENCE OF A MICROBURST IN THE AREA. THE FOLLOWING ACCOUNT IS FROM THE MARYBOROUGH CHRONICLE OF 23/01/95. FIERCE WINDS RIPPED THROUGH ISOLATED SECTIONS OF HERVEY BAY EARLY ON SATURDAY MORNING LEAVING FIVE PEOPLE INJURED AND SEVERAL BUILDINGS AND CARAVANS DAMAGED. A SPOKESMAN FOR HERVEY BAY POLICE,SERGENT STEVE IMHOFF, SAID THE MINI-CYCLONE SWEPT THROUGH HERVEY BAY ABOUT 1AM CAUSING EXTENSIVE DAMAGE TO HOUSES BUSINESS PREMISES AND CARAVANS. ONE OF THE WORST HIT AREAS OF THE BAY WAS PIALBA CARAVAN PARK. FIVE PEOPLE FROM THE PARK WERE TAKEN TO HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT FOLLOWING INJURIES SUSTAINED FROM THE BRIEF STORM. ONE WOMAN WAS TRANSFERRED TO THE MARYBOROUGH BASE HOSPITAL WITH SUSPECTED SPLEEN DAMAGE. A SIX YEAR OLD BRISBANE BOY, TERRY HESSEY RECIEVED SIX STICHES TO HIS FACE AFTER BEING INJURED WHEN HE WAS THROWN FROM ONE END OF HIS CARAVAN TO THE OTHER . HIS FATHER , BRIAN HESSEY , SAID THE FAMILY WAS AWOKEN IN THE EARLY HOURS OF SATURDAY MORNING WHEN GALE FORCE WINDS ROCKED THEIR CARAVAN. MR HESSEY SAID HE MANAGED TO CATCH HIS SON WHEN HE WAS CATPULTED FROM HIS BED AS THE VAN WAS BLOWN ON ITS SIDE. HIS WIFE PATRICIA SAID NEIGHBOURS HAD TO FREE THE FAMILY FROM THE VAN AFTER IT HAD BLOWN OVER IN THE STORM.  THE PEOPLE IN NEIGHBOURING CARAVANS CAME OUT  TO HELP AS SOON AS THEY HEARD THE NOISE. THEY HAD TO WRENCH THE DOOR OPEN SO WE COULD CLIMB OUT. IT WAS SO DISTRESSING
column11: ESPECIALLY WITH THE WIND AND RAIN AND IT WAS DARK AND WE WERE SO DISORIENTATED
column12: PATRICIA SAID . ANOTHER FAMILY STAYING AT THE CARAVAN PARK HAD A LUCKY ESCAPE  WHEN THEIR CARAVAN WAS EXTENSIVE DAMAGED BY THE STORM. RON WEST AND HIS FAMILY WOKE TO THE SOUND OF THEIR ANNEX BEING RIPPED TO SHREDS BY THE FIERCE WINDS. SHERON HERVEY, THE WESTS DAUGHTER WAS STAYING IN  THE ANNEX OF THE VAN. SHE AWOKE WHEN THE BRANCH OF A TREE FELL THROUGH THE ANNEX AND LANDED ON HER. SPOKESMAN FOR HERVEY BAY AMBULANCE, GRAHAM COOPER , SAID MOST OF THE INJURIES SUSTAINED DURING THE STORM WERE CUT AND ABRASIONS. ONE WOMAN  WAS TAKEN TO HERVEY BAY HOSPITAL SUFFERING SHOCK. STATE EMERGENCY SERVICE SERVICES CONTROLLER COL PIERCE,SAID THE STORM WAS LIKE A MINI-TORNADO. IT WAS LIKE THE WATER SPOUTS WE EXPERIENCED RECENTLY EXCEPT IT WAS OVER LAND. THAT'S WHY THE DAMAGE SEEMS TO HAVE OCCURRED IN AREAS COVERING ABOUT 50 SQUARE FEET AT A TIME. MR PEARCE SAID THE STORM BROUGHT "FEROCIOUS" WINDS
column13: BUT DAMAGE WAS SUSTAINED IN ISOLATED AREAS. "WE WERE CALLED OUT TO THREE HOUSES IN POINT VERNON AND ONE IN SCARNESS WHICH HAD ALL SUSTAINED EXTENSIVE ROOF DAMAGE. THE POLES IN THE ROOF HAD ALL BEEN TORN OFF AND DUMPED NEARBY
column14: AND YET NEIGHOURING HOUSES HARDLY HAD ENOUGH WIND TO STIR PAPER."  MR PEARCE SAID THE DAMAGED HOUSES WERE IN DIAMOND COURT
column15: APLIN STREET AND BELL STREET POINT VERNON
column16: AND FRESHWATER STREET SCARNESSS. BUSINESS PREMISES IN TORQUAY ROAD AND  MAIN STREET PIALBA
column17: WERE SELECTIVELY TARGETED BY THE WHIRLWIND. THE MOST EXTENSIVE DAMAGE WAS SUSTAINED BY BOYS FAMILY DEPARTMENT STORE IN MAIN STREET. A 30M BY 5 M SECTION OF BRICK WALL  AT THE SIDE OF THE BUILDING COLLAPSED DURING THE HEIGHT OF THE STORM
column18: AND THE ROOF WAS ALSO DAMAGED. PART OF THE ROOF OF A NEIGHBOURING STORE WAS AALSO BLOWN OFF IN THE GALE.  AT  ST JOHNS GARDENS IN TORQUAY ROAD
column19: SAY IT WITH FLOWERS LOST PART OF ITS ROOF. ACROSS THE ROAD DAVID'S  ULTRASOUND SUFFERED CEILING DAMAGE WHEN PART OF ITS ROOF WAS BLOWN AWAY. THE SUNSEEKER MOTEL AT SCARNESS ALSO HAD EXTENSIVE ROOF DAMAGE. MR  PEARCE SAID ALTHOUGH MUCH OF THE STORM IN ISOLATED POCKETS
column20: THERE WAS SUBSTANTIAL DAMAGE TO SIGNS AND WINDOWS THROUGHT THE AREA."

Comments: Possible tornado observed at Mount Kynoch (near Toowoomba) at around 6pm AEST. No damage reported. 01-12-1995. Thunderstorm over the Darling Downs with a suspected tornado sighted at Mt Kynock about 8 kilometres northeast of the Toowoomba Aerodrome.

Tornado observed at Rockhampton Airport around 6pm AEST. No damage reported. 23-12-1995. Observer at Rockhampton WSO sighted a suspected tornado.  Funnel passed over a sparsely populated area and as a result no reports of damage or confirmation.

Tornado observed just east of Dalby around 11:50am AEST. No damage reported. 11/12/96: report from Army pilot: ...   " a funnel cloud to the ground approximately 1/4 to 1/2 mile south of heavy rain. ( thunderstorm just east of Dalby.) "...cloud lasted about 15 minutes. "
Possible tornado at Yukan around 3:30pm AEST. Report of a swath of damage through a cane field.  T.C. Ita was located near Townsville at thew time of the event

Tornado observed at Springmount, a property near Goondiwindi, around 12pm AEST. Report of small trees uprooted and large branches ripped off trees. 01/05/99: 02:10 utc.   Seven photos received from Springmount"

Comments: Possible tornado at Cedar Pocket around 4:30pm AEST. Report of swirling debris lifted approximately 300 feet in the air and a very badly damaged timber house. Storm Spotter reported that tree damage in the area suggested a tornado occurred. 08-11-1999.  Approx 06:30utc. Timber house at Cedar Pocket (approx. 6 km east of Gympie) very badly damaged by winds associated with a thunderstorm. Witnesses described swirling debris lifted 300ft into the air, although no funnel was sighted. These witnesses stated   a friend reported a V-shaped funnel cloud on the outskirts of Gympie." Storm chasers reported pattern of tree damage suggested a tornado."

Tornado observed near Bethania around 5pm AEST. Report from eyewitness included severe damage to outbuildings, some damage to a house. Kennels, pergola and a shed were destroyed. Some big roof beams were found over 400 metres away. Other damage in the area included brick stable blocks levelled and houses unroofed. Many trees were damaged and large ones uprooted. No images of the damage were available, so the Fujita number was limited to F1. 10/12/99: Storm chasers reported a swathe of property and tree damage stretching from just south of Boonah to Redland Bay, due to strong winds associated with a  thunderstorm. Storm spotter and newspaper reports of large hail. { 5 cm at Brunswick Heads (NSW); 2---3 cm at Stephens (Gold Coast);  Golfball size at Park Ridge, Shailer Park and other areas south of Brisbane. [2 separate cells]

Possible tornado at Rockhampton around 2:30pm AEST. Reports of up to 5 tornadoes in the Rockhampton area, though unable to confirm the occurance of all of these. Estimated damage bill over $200,000 with widespread tree damage and roofing damage to some houses. Reports of a large truck alledgedly being lifted and thrown about 50 metres and images of a large uprooted tree that was lifted onto the roof of a house. Golfball sized hail reported in the outer suburbs of Rockhampton. A 78km/h wind gust was recorded at the Rockhampton Airport Automatic Weather Station.  02/11/2000: Severe storm tore a path of destruction through North Rockhampton suburbs with reports of up to 5 tornadoes (evidence of at least 1 confirmed by the Bureau). Estimated damage bill over $200,000 with widespread tree damage and roofing damage to some houses. Golfball sized hail reported in the outer suburbs with wind estimates to 80kts but only 42kts actually measured at the Rockhampton airport. A large truck was lifted and thrown about 50m.
Tornado observed approximately 35 kilometres southwest of Longreach (along Jundah Road) around 6:30pm AEST. No damage reported. Tornado sighted 35km southwest of Longreach.

Tornado observed at Grandchester at around 3pm AEST. No damage reported. Partially formed funnel cloud photographed by Storm Spotter, Anthony Cornelius. A thunderstorm squall line moved across southeast Qld during the afternoon. Oakey recorded a 50 knot wind gust and a tormado was observed near Granchester.

several houses unroofed. Heavy shower of hail also fell. People heard a roaring noise and the damage followed a well defined path with trees uprooted or with branches torn off. Walkerville; several houses unroofed. Heavy shower of hail also fell.

Comments: Within the track of the cyclone, the force of the wind was terrific; buildings damaged and trees uprooted. Time not recorded. A number of severe thunderstorms resulted in damage over Adelaide, Gawler, Tanunda, Lyndoch, Meningie, Kadina, Moonta, Port Wakefield, Snowtown, Balaklava, Port Adelaide and Dublin. 4 tornados seem likely; suburb Port Adelaide/Kilkenny, Gawler (these 2 could be from the same storm because the one at Kilkenny, travelled from NE to SW), Kadina and Dublin.   Also in Gawler hail resulted in windows broken, gardens and crops damaged.  In Tanunda, hail destroyed the currant crop and damaged the vines; sheets of iron blown about. The hail was followed by heavy rain resulting in flooding which added to the hail damage. Lyndock; windows broken,  crops damaged.   Heavy rain and wind damage near Barunga Gap (trees uprooted or snapped off).

A terrific duststorm occurred and was followed by a cyclone which wrecked several buildings. Time not recorded but the tornado was probably associated with the passage of a pre frontal trough, with thunderstorms, that passed through Port Germein at 2pm. Port Germein; thunderstorm at 2pm. Several sheds and outbuildings demolished, fences levelled and roofs blown off.   Wirrabara; A terrific duststorm occurred and was followed by a cyclone which wrecked several buildings (time not recorded).

A severe duststorm occurred and was followed by a cyclone which did a great amount of damage to property.  Time not recorded but estimated from Lyndoch (3pm) and Nuriootpa (3:45pm) reports. Thunderstorms occurred on a pre frontal trough. Tanunda; A severe duststorm occurred and was followed by a cyclone which did a great amount of damage to property.  Time not recorded but estimated from Lyndoch (3pm) and Nuriootpa (3:45pm) reports.

The cyclone" occurred about 15 minutes after a southwest wind change. Port Wakefield; A strong northerly wind blew for much of the day. About 2pm a thunderstorm was reported. The wind "fell away" before a vigerous southwest change at about 3pm. The cyclone struck the town about 6:15pm
column11: unroofing several houses and causing injuries to occupants."

Comments: Thunderstorm with marble size hail. Great devastation over a strip of timbered country. Many gums, some over 100 years old, uprooted while others 2 feet in diameter were broken. A number of outbuildings were unroofed. Adelaide; several short sharp thunderstorms with hail, rain and violent gusty winds over the plains and hills. A little after 7am, two rows of big gums on Woodville Rd at Woodville were considerably damaged with huge limbs torn away and hurled across the road. Tramshed and some other buildings unroofed at Brighton.  Tornado likely at Coromandel Valley at 7pm.  Thunderstorms at Verdun (Grunthal) and Mt Barker resulted in heavy hail showers size generally the size of marbles, but in Verdun many windows were broken and other damage done.

funnel cloud observed, stables unroofed at one farm. A house was unroofed on a second farm.  Time only given as afternoon.  A second report mentions a whirlwind. Mount Gambier; funnel cloud observed, stables unroofed at one farm. A house was unroofed on a second farm.  Time only given as afternoon.  A second report mentions a whirlwind.

A tornado caused a track of damage not more than a mile (1600 metres) wide. Sheds blown down, trees stripped of large branches, houses unroofed. Time not recorded. Renmark; A tornado caused a track of damage not more than a mile (1600 metres) wide. Sheds blown down, trees stripped of large branches, houses unroofed. Time not recorded.

a cyclone accompanied by a thunderstorm passed over the town and did considerable damage. Several verandahs blown away and houses unroofed. Marree (Hergott Springs); a cyclone accompanied by a thunderstorm passed over the town and did considerable damage. Several verandahs blown away and houses unroofed.
funnel cloud observed. A property suffered damage to machinery and stables about midday. The cyclone" lasted only a few minutes

Comments: Immense damage. Path width 100 to 200 at time of most intense damage where practically everything in its path was levelled. It broadened to about 500m before lifting off the ground as it passed over a house, then grounded again snapping off large trees (diameter of 50-60cm) and carrying them up to 20m. Traffic was completely blocked on some roads for some time because of fallen timber. Meadows; severe windstorm and heavy hail. Funnel cloud observed. Path width of immense" damage about 100 to 200m mentioned. Thunderstorm assumed. No other damage or storms mentioned on the day. Time not recorded but morning mentioned."

Gaol lost its roof which was blown over a neighbouring house. Myall trees 40 to 50 ft high were torn out of the ground and in some cases carried 50 yards. Several buildings were extensively damaged during the storm which lasted 10 to 15 minutes. Iron Knob; a storm "more in the nature of a typhoon or tornado". Gaol lost its roof which was blown over a neighbouring house. Myall trees 40 to 50 ft high were torn out of the ground and in some cases carried 50 yards. Several buildings were extensively damaged during the storm which lasted 10 to 15 minutes.

Wind uprooted trees in all directions. The storm extended for only one mile (1600 metres) in width and could be easily traced by the fallen trees.  Described as a cyclone. Time not recorded. Afternoon mentioned. Kybybolite (near Naracoorte); severe hailstorm damaged orchards. Heavy rain also occurred. Wind uprooted trees in all directions. The storm extended for only one mile (1600 metres) in width and could be easily traced by the fallen trees.  Described as a cyclone. Time not recorded. Afternoon mentioned.
The track of the storm looked like some mighty roller had passed along
column11: levelling everything. Huge trees were torn out -- one tree had four big limbs about 6 ft from the ground torn off and carried several chains (about 100 to 150 metres) and smashed." At Wild Dog Hill (just north of Port Wakefield) significant damage inflicted on a house and outhouse and many trees uprooted.     Time given as evening. "An undoubted cyclone" with a track of less than half a mile (800 metres) was evident in parts from Maitland to the top of  Gulf St. Vincent near Port Arthur. Much damage occurred on the opposite side of the gulf at Wild Dog Hill. Time given as evening."

Comments: On a property near Burra; 2 tornados; trees uprooted, stripped or broken in the centre. A heavy trolly was carried some distance. All sheds and outhouses were unroofed, several windmills blown over. One tornado passed over the dam, carried water about 50 feet into the air, and as a result the gauge showed a depth of at least 2 feet less than immediately before the storm. Cost of damage about 1,000 pounds. Time not recorded. Severe hail and thunderstorms occurred over parts of central and northern agricultural areas of the state; crops, vineyards and orchards were much damaged. Localities include Alford and Wallaroo (YP), Riverton, Marrabel (24mm in 20 minutes), Gulnare and Burra (MN). Near Burra 2 tornados caused much destruction.  Time not recorded but a severe thunderstorm reported in Adelaide at 1:30pm.

A destructive whirlwind caused damage to land which it crossed. Yankalilla; hail the size of pigeon eggs. A whirlwind was mentioned. (possible funnel cloud)  Damage caused to land which the whirlwind crossed.

a violent cyclone, lasting only a few minutes, wrought considerable damage. North Walkerville and Nailsworth; a violent cyclone, lasting only a few minutes, wrought considerable damage. A house in Nailsworth was unroofed and chimney blown down, the roof ended up intact in a paddock 100 yards away. Other houses suffered damage. Stables in North Walkerville were unroofed and fencing levelled.

Many trees uprooted and portions of others torn off. About 1 mile (1600 metres) of telegraph poles were bent about. Electric wires were cut in several places by flying sheets of iron from dwellings. Balaklava; "a cyclone" swept across the counrty and left in its wake torn up trees and damaged sheds and house roofs. Many trees uprooted and portions of others torn off. NPWS officers Heather Kriesl and Trevor Nailsmith witnessed the storm.  Tornado occurrence deduced from description of damage path. 'There was just this incredible roar of wind.  It picked up the red dust and you could not see across the road'.  About 50 trees were felled or damaged, but no damage to the park office or toilets.  The damage path was narrow but at least 3 km long. A likely tornado at Bool Lagoon Conservation Park (LSE);  3 Jan 1991. Tornado occurrence deduced from description of damage path.

Details on damage path are a little vague and contradictory, however, two of three witnesses reported seeing a funnel cloud and all three estimated the wind at about 100 knots. Strong gusty winds, blowing dust and rain were observed with the storm which moved NW to SE.   Damage area to the west and south of Karoonda.  One house on edge of town lost half it's roof;  sheds were unroofed, sheets of corrugated iron blown around and many trees broken or blown over.  600-700 m of fencing 4 km SW of town was flattened.  On a property 15 km south of town, a farm building made of cement bricks was badly damaged. Tornado at Karoonda (ML);  3 Jan 1991. Details on damage path are a little vague and contradictory, however, two of three witnesses reported seeing a funnel cloud and all three estimated the wind at about 100 knots. Long lived tornadic supercell;  22 Jan 1991.  Storm tracked thru Wandearah, Bundaleer Forest,  Jamestown,  Pandappa Station.  See Tech Note for more.

10 stobie poles at Carrackalinga snapped off as a waterspout crossed the coast. The steel sections of the poles were rusted. Waterspout moved onshore at Carrickalinga (GAA);  16 June 1991. 10 stobie poles snapped off as a waterspout crossed the coast. The steel sections of the poles were rusted.

Tornado between Mt Torrens and Rockleigh. Damage mostly confined to trees although a shed was involved. Tornado between Mt Torrens and Rockleigh. Severe wind gusts at Adelaide and Parafield (GAA/MLR);  A significant line of showers and thunderstorms passed over Adelaide and the Mt Lofty Ranges and southern Mid North. The Willaston Hotel lost a section of its roof. A roof was blown off in the inner city and billboards destroyed. Large hail reported near Rockleigh.

Some uncertainty as to why this event was classified a tornado.  The storm came from the west or northwest.  The strong gusts lasted about 5 minutes and occurred with rain and small hail.  Sheets of iron were removed from 3 houses;  a home-made carport was destroyed;  about 2 dozen trees were downed in the general area;  Also many tree limbs down.  Damage path was described as narrow, about 1 1/2 km wide.  Heavy rain with the storm - caused bowls to be abandoned! Tornado at Kalangadoo (LSE);  4 April 1992

About 30 large redgums in grazing country had branches torn off.  Limbs of 15-45 cm in diameter were broken off.  Damage was strewn along the damage track, with some debris carried 100-150 metres from the parent tree.  One mature gum was snapped off 4-6 metres above the ground (where trunk was nearly 1 metre in diameter).  Open grazing country to the west of the damaged area.  Photo provided (see file).  Dimensions of damage path provided by the Paltridges. Tornado at Krongart, south southwest of Penola (LSE);  9 June 1992. About 30 large redgums in grazing country had branches torn off.

Details provided by Mrs Barnett.  Path described as 1 1/4 miles long and 80-100 yards wide.  Two trees were uprooted; two were broken off half way up and numerous others had their tops taken off. More than 50 houses were damaged, several suffering major structural damage.  See Fig 2(a) of Met Note 207.  Damage bill estimated as $500,000. Tornado at Salisbury, Adelaide;  12 Aug 1992.  Over 50 houses were damaged over a 4 km track.  See Met Note 207 for more detail.  Several severe convective gusts with front - need to check radar to identify storm cells.

Damage was confined to native vegetation, so monetary loss was minimal.  Damage path about 2 km long, around 50 metres wide and orientated WSW- ENE. Tornado near Auburn (MN);  12 Aug 1992.  See Met Note for more detail.

Graphic photo of the tornado provided by Wayne McCallum.  No details on track length or width.  While there was a lot of hail damage, have not been able to locate any wind damage in the area. Time uncertain. Tornado at Penfield, Adelaide;  20 Nov 1992. Time uncertain, thought to be about 4:30pm. Tornado damage was surveyed on 21 Sept.  The affected area was mostly cleared grazing land with some vineyards along the western side of Long Gully Road.  Most of the damage was to large gum trees.  A shearing shed lost it's entire roof and a hay shed part of it's roof.  One sheet of roofing iron was found wrapped around a stobie pole.  Another sheet was found 300 metres southeast of the shed impaled on a trellis wire in the vineyard.  The wire had made a 20 cm cut into the iron sheet. Tornado near Angaston;  19 Sept 1993.  Covered with Wind Advice

Tornado cut swathe through the Renmark Golf Course.  15 trees were completely uprooted and numerous others lost limbs.  One golfer described that 'he heard the wind coming'. Storm description provided by property owner (Ian Bidstrip). Area visited briefly by D. Griffiths and J. Pethick several weeks later. Damage path started about 1 km east of Mintaro, and extended SE over 2-2.5 km. The roof of a 100 year old stone building (shearers quarters), including the timbers and ceiling, was torn off. The main section of the roof ended up 300 metres to the southeast. Stoves and fridges in the building were shifted around. Shearers in the building described it going 'deathly quiet', then there was a noise that sounded like a jet engine had started up next door.  They felt it was lucky no-one was killed. Ian said he lost lots of trees as well, some up to 120 years old. Witness estimated time as 1230Z, radar suggests closer to 1245Z. Tornado near Mintaro (MN);  22 Sept 1998. Damage to shearers quarters and trees. Path 50 m wide and 2-2.5 km long. Rated at low end of F1.

Nine houses suffered major roof damage, many of those had the roof completely removed. A lady sufferd minor head injuries when the ceiling of her house collpased. A relatively slow moving front caused a period of heavy rain about the lower west coast and a tornado in Roleystone. The trail of damage extended discontinuously for at least 2km, being about 50m wide along a bearing from 310 to 130 degrees. A few houses sustained significant roof damage. Being through semi-rural area most of the impact was to trees with some large trees snapped off at various heights above the base. While most trees fell to the ESE there were some at other directions. Roof debris indicated a clockwise circulation. The event occurred at 2:30pm and witnesses described the typical roar/jet engine sound associated with previous tornado events. A preliminary estimate of winds based on some of the most severe tree damage was put at 150-200 km/h by wind engineer Geoff Boughton.

Comments:
A tornado passed through Bunbury south of the city centre at about 10:50 WST on a cell in the post frontal airmass. Damage along a narrow WSW-ENE path of several kilometres. SES report four houses with roof completely off and about seven others major roof damage and 20 others with minor roof damage. Geoff Boughton did an inspection and reported evidence of rotation in damage path. Major roof damage was to tin roofed houses while tiled houses were mainly damaged from debris impact. Width about 30m extending along a discontinuous path of about 3 km (from the coast to the cemetery). Eye-witnesses report characteristic 'roaring' sound and swirling debris without funnel cloud. One report from someone 50m away who was totally oblivious to it all and could not tell that anything had happened. Followed by a large quantity of hail. Estimated wind at roof level 100-140 km/h (120-160km/h at 10m) equivalent of F1 tornado. A moderate front passed across during the morning causing a tornado at Bunbury and severe wind gusts at coastal sites.

column11: there was some small hail and several claps of thunder. Damage path (NW-SE) was about 100-130m wide and about 3km in length but could have been longer. Between Katanning and Kojonup: Tree damage was reported as well as fences down and roofs ripped of houses. 4 silos were blown away and smashed. Very little rain was reported with the tornado. The damage path was about 3-4km in length and had a maximum width of about 100m. An eyewitness reported seeing the tornado (funnel cloud extending to the ground) after it had passed through this property on the Kojonup-Katanning road near the intersection with Marron Pool road. The cell which spawned the tornado is evident on the Albany radar with the strongest reflectivities at 0905 UTC between Katanning and Kojonup. A convergence line produced a wind gust of 53 knots (98 km/h) at Cape Naturaliste at 1537 WST (23/06) and 52 knots (96 km/h) at Rottnest Island at 1611 WST (23/06).

Up to 6 people reported injured, 2 requiring hospitalisation. Widespread media coverage with video footage and damage photos on media websites. Supercell thunderstorm and associated tornado developed near Lennox Head early on the morning of 3/6/10, storm tracked north to Byron bay then turned offshore.

The gust of 194km/h was measured on the Bureau AWS at Scottsdale. The tornado appeared to pass very close by the AWS. Nearby, an old bus was blown over and a child's swing set was moved about 50 metres.  The tornado passed nearby the house of the Bureau's co-operative observer who saw tree branches and sheets of corrugated iron being blown past the AWS about 30 to 40 metres away. There was extensive tree damage to at least one property near the tornado track. NULL

Tornado observed at The Summit (near Stanthorpe) around 12pm AEST. Media articles report of trees pulled from the ground (10 acres of pine trees flattened), two houses demolished (Queenslander alledgedly lifed off its stumps), fruit crops battered, hail netting shredded and sheds destroyed. A major severe convective outbreak. A confirmed tornado of F1-F2 intensity was photographed around midday at The Summit, near Stanthorpe, where it shredded hail nets protecting a cherry crop, lifted a Queenslander house off its stumps, and completely destroyed another house and a pumping shed. Two other suspected tornadoes occurred at Mt Nebo and Biggenden.  A major hailstorm occurred on the Gold Coast with the worst affected areas being Currumbin, Palm Beach, and Coolangatta. Hail was golf ball to cricket ball sized. 400 homes were damaged, many cars were written off, and birds and animals at the Currumbin Wildlife Sanctuary were killed. A Qantas jet was badly damaged after taking off into the hailstorm. Later, golf ball hail also disrupted the Indy 500 car race.  Another major severe storm moved from the Samford / Mt Nebo area through Brisbane’s northern suburbs and Redcliffe. This storm produced hail up to golf ball size and significant wind damage, particularly in the Samford / Mt Nebo area where 90 homes were damaged. A damage track through forest near Mt Nebo was observed from the air suggesting the storm may have been tornadic.%D Other severe storms occurred in the Esk/Laidley/Ipswich area (tree and power line damage, some roof damage), the south Burnett (tree and roofing damage at Eidsvold and Blackbutt, golf ball hail in the Nanango and Burnett Heads areas), Biggenden (possible tornado – a damage track 500m wide and a kilometer long), Baralaba (golf ball hail), Warwick (hail to 5cm, 100 km/h wind gust measured, some flash flooding), and as far north as Rockhampton (94 km/h wind gust measured).%D Insurance claims for the event totaled $15-20 million with 772 SES jobs on the Gold Coast alone.

Possible tornado or funnel cloud(s) observed at Sundown Observatory near Ballandean at around 11:20 am. No direct tornado related damage reported. A line of storms produced damaging wind gusts over a wide area of southern inland Queensland. At Charleville, trees were uprooted, 3 power lines brought down, and a railway building was unroofed. A wind gust of 100 km/h was measured. Other recorded wind gusts were 118 km/h at Roma and 100 km/h at St George. Trees were also brought down and houses unroofed in the Tara area. A block of flats was partially unroofed in Toowoomba.

A stormspotter reportedly sighted the tornado. Direction of path was from west to east with a length of 2km. The spotter reported tree branches snapped, trees uprooted, roofing tiles lifted and damage to buildings. The passage of a deep low and associated cold front across the SWLD produced some damage around Harvey where a possible tornado occurred.

An eyewitness reported seeing the tornado shortly after 10pm on the 26th from his property on Bibanup Court, Hillman. He reported a general west to east track with a speed approximately 30-40 km/h. A cold front moved through the SWLD late on the 26th with a secondary front on the 27th. SES received a total of 64 calls for assistance from across the metropolitan area over a 12 hour period.

A suspected weak tornado at 10pm Thursday night caused a narrow trail of damage in Perth's southern suburb of Parkwood including the felling of a large tree that fell on a house trapping a man who required hospitalisation. A front and significant cold pool caused widespread severe winds across the SWLD and Goldfields.

Comments: Tornado observed at Bundamba (east of Ipswich) at around 4:30pm AEST. Media articles report of a half-finished house destroyed at Bundamba and other homes having some roof damage, though there are no images of the damage and therefore confidence in the assigned Fujita number is not high. Report of damage at the Racecourse Hotel due to considerable airborne debris, including a mango smashing a Hungry Jacks sign. A wind gust of 111km/h was recorded at the Amberley Automatic Weather Station. A severe thunderstorm moved through Ipswich and Brisbane producing wind damage and some flash flooding. A tornado was reported from Bundamba, as well as golf ball sized hail. Amberley aerodrome recorded a highest wind gust of 60 knots (111 km/h).

Tornado observed at Mount Mee/Ocean View at around 5pm AEST (exact time of the event is unknown and was estimated from satellite imagery). Reports of large trees uprooted and industrial bins lifted and thrown approximately 6 metres. Another line of severe storms moved through southeast Queensland. A supercell tracked through the Somerset Dam/Woodford area, producing a tornado which was sighted at Mt. Mee / Ocean View, east of Somerset Dam - this uprooted large trees and lifted industrial bins and threw them 6 metres. Wind damage to trees occurred in southwest Brisbane.

Tornado observed at Beenleigh at around 4:20pm AEST. Numerous damage reports were received from across southeast Queensland, though it is difficult to ascertain if any damage was due to the tornado. Yet another line of severe thunderstorms moved across southeast Queensland. Widespread damage resulted, particularly in the Brisbane (wind) and Gympie (hail) areas. A tornado was sighted near Beenleigh. The roof of an entire unit block at New Farm was torn off. Two young girls were injured by a falling tree on a university campus at St Lucia. Measured wind gusts included Cape Moreton – 55 knots (102 km/h), Cleveland – 59 knots (109 km/h), and Banana Bank – 66 knots (122 km/h). More than 100,000 homes and businesses were blacked out. Elsewhere golf ball hail occurred at Stanthorpe and Woodford, while hail to cricket ball size caused considerable damage at Gympie.

Possible tornado around Rosedale and the Baffle Creek at around 4:50pm AEST. Reports of houses unroofed and trees snapped in Rosedale. A shed was alledgedly lifted and carried about a kilometre. A garage was totally destroyed. A water tank of unknown origin was dumped next to the dam of a property. Golf ball hail also accompanied the storm, destroying watermelon and passionfruit crops. There are no images of the damage and therefore confidence in the assigned Fujita number is not high and it is possible that it could have been an F2 event. Severe storms affected the Wide Bay and Burnett district. A possible tornado struck the Rosedale area (50km NW of Bundaberg) – houses were unroofed, trees snapped, and a shed was lifted and carried about a kilometre. Golf ball sized hail also accompanied the storm. Hail the size of cricket balls was reported from another storm near Boompa (southeast of Biggenden), while hail damage to mango and avocado crops was reported from Childers.

NULL A trough moving across the state triggered showers and thunderstorms about the Riverland during the afternoon and evening. A tornado was reported at Winkie in the Riverland causing damage to property and vegetation.

There were also damage reports from the Riverland, including a report of a “mini tornado”. Thunderstorms developed in the NWP during the afternoon, producing damaging wind gusts and local flash flooding. The system tracked east-southeastwards across the Flinders, Mid North, Riverland and Murraylands districts in the evening with most thunderstorms clearing the eastern border in the early hours of the morning.

Redbanks, near Mallala : Another cell spawned a tornado at about 10:00 am, which cut swathe of damage through a farm property. Besser block stable destroyed, roof blown off, fences destroyed, trees ripped out and fences blown over. A report of a big tree lying across railway track 6 km away. Damage estimated as F0 to low end F1? One witness captured the tornado on camera. Cold front with several associated bands of convection tracked across Adelaide and southern SA during the morning. Two severe cells.

One long-lived thunderstorm, which formed just ahead of the cold front, tracked across LSE, from near Robe, through Penola and into western Vic, during the late afternoon/early evening. The storm spawned a tornado, which ripped a narrow path of damage through the town of Penola. About forty buildings were damaged, several homes suffered severe damage, rendering them uninhabitable. The bowling clubhouse was destroyed, hardware store unroofed and several businesses suffered smashed windows and collapsed walls. Damage path was 6 km long, but only 40-50 metres wide, consistent with high end F1, possibly low end F2 intensity. Early estimates put the damage bill at several millions of dollars. Fortunately, there were no serious injuries.%D %D A second tornado spawned from another cell damaged farm buildings and trees on a property at Claywells. Several long lived thunderstorms tracked through the South East of SA ahead of a strong cold front which tracked across southern SA (including Adelaide) Also deep convection aligned along the front.

NULL The passage of a cold front during the day produced several waterspouts around the Perth area and a likely tornado in Bunbury. A narrow swathe of damage around 700 m long was reported from the Bunbury suburb of Usher around 1 pm WST. DFES reported about 10 call outs for damage to trees, fences, patio, tiles and ridge capping. The Serpentine radar image at 0450 UTC showed an enhanced cell approaching the coast to the south of the city with an unusual velocity signal at an elevation of approximately 10 000 feet. The environment was more unstable than the usual winter time front. The cell formed over the ocean to the west of Bunbury where CAPE values in ACCESS R fields were between 200 and 500 J/Kg. The storm cell formed in the warm air mass ahead of the front on a northerly to northwest convergence line. ACCESS R fields indicated some areas of overlap of shear, instability and up motion.

A severe thunderstorm near Kalgoorlie caused some injuries and significant damage at KCGM (Super Pit). Below is an extract from their damage report: The extent of the damage caused by a severe thunderstorm at KCGM on Friday is still being assessed. Around 3.30pm on 4th December, tornado-like conditions swept through parts of the operation, causing significant damage. The mobile fleet maintenance workshops were the worst hit; with major structural damage, power, communication and water services being cut. The Open Pit administration office was also damaged, with the entrance doors being blown in and internal ceiling panels collapsing. A number of large trees were also uprooted and power lines brought down. KCGM General Manager Ian Butler said the storm was so intense it was lucky there weren't more serious injuries. One person received a fracture in his foot

A clear and narrow damage path was noted during this event which is supported by the radar signatures at the time. The strongest evidence to support tornadic activity is a gust of 213km/h at Kurnell AWS at 10.33am, with SES reports confirming the removal of rooves from houses and uprooting of mature trees in the area. A range of images from online social and news media also show damage to a number of properties in Kurnell, an over turned truck, and the partial removal of the roof of the desalination plant. The strength of the observed wind gust and onsite visual evidence of the damage place this tornado in the F2 category. Later reports emerged (~11.40am) from head office media stating a number of callers from Bondi Beach sighting a tornado. Based on radar data at this time and no specific damage reports it was most likely offshore. LGA: Sutherland Shire. NULL

A highly organised supercell thunderstorm was evident on radar west of Jerrys Plains around 3pm. This cell tracked slowly east towards Singleton by 4.30pm, then northeast towards Nabiac by 6.30pm. Doppler radar showed a clearly defined low level velocity couplet lasting for over an hour with this storm, weakening once the cell tracked past Singleton. The SES reported significant damage at Doyles Creek and Singleton, including some roofs partially or fully lifted off, trees down on roads, and some trees crushing cars. Secondhand reports (friend of a storm spotter) were received of tornado damage at the Darley and Coolmore Horse Studs and mines including trees ripped out of the ground. The location of this report is consistent with the position of the low level velocity couplet. One photo on social media shows a mature tree with large branches broken off and a wire fence bent over at Jerrys Plains, with all debris aligned in the same direction. Tornadic activity seems likely but difficult to estimate path lengths or EF scales without more detailed investigation. NULL

A strong line of fast moving thunderstorms, possibly supercells, moved through the Forbes Creek/Hoskinstown area late on Saturday night (approximately 11.30pm), spawning at least one tornado. A damage survey conducted onsite showed numerous Eucalypts had been snapped and Pines uprooted, a kit home damaged, shearing shed demolished, and front wall of a double brick structure destroyed. The estimated width of the damage swathe was 150m, with the SES reporting damage along a 3km path. Other reports from the SES include major structural damage to 6 properties in the Forbes Creek/Hoskinstown area, with a number of trees down on access roads. Numerous media articles (SMH, ABC, Canberra Times) were written for this event, and photos posted on the Queanbeyan Facebook page showing significant damage to structures and properties. Estimated strength: EF2. NULL

Comments: It was concluded that damage in parts of Townsville matched the specifications of an F2 tornado. The evidence used to come to this conclusion included images of roofs being torn off frame houses, large trees being uprooted and some light objects appearing to have become missiles. The tornado of the event happened in parts of Townsville between the airport and the suburbs of Vincent and Gulliver. Radar evidence indicated the presence of a Bounded Weak Echo Region, which is a characteristic signature of a supercell thunderstorm. The damage assessment conducted by James Cook University indicated a path of damage that correlates with the passage of the supercell signature on radar. The report also noted that tree damage appeared to be convergent across the area, which corresponds more closely to the damage pattern associated with the passage of a tornado. Significant wind gust observations were also recorded around Townsville Airport during the event, including a 3 second wind gust of 111km/h at 5:07am AEST at the Automatic Weather Station and a wind gust of 135km/h at the Dines anemometer. NULL

The report of a tornado at Inkerman (southeast of Ayr) was submitted by a local cane farmer to the Bureau of Meteorology office in Townsville on the 25 January 2013. The exact time of the tornado was unknown, but it is suspected to have occurred on the night of 23 January 2013 or the morning of 24 January 2013. The farmer reported a 200m swath of destruction through his cane field and that the damage appeared to have occurred in a circular fashion. The environment was conducive for tornadoes at the time of the event and radar indicated that there may have been cells with a potential mesocyclone in the area during the assumed time of the tornado event. No Rapid Damage Assessment was conducted in the area by Queensland Fire and Emergency Services to confirm the passage of a tornado, no Doppler radar data was available and no images of the reported damage were provided, so it was difficult to confirm whether the damage could be attributed to a tornado. NULL

No damage was reported from the area and no Doppler radar data was available, so it was difficult to confirm whether the recorded wind gust could be attributed to the occurrence of a tornado. NULL

It was concluded that damage in parts of Burrum Heads (associated with the tornado that caused damage to coastal areas of the town) largely matched the specifications of an F2 tornado, though there was also evidence of damage matching that of an F3 tornado. The evidence used to come to this conclusion included images of a roof and some walls torn off a frame house in Sunrise Crescent and that a cabin in the local caravan park appeared to have been lifted and thrown some distance. The second confirmed tornado that occurred at Burrum Heads during the TC OSwald tornado event. The tornado caused considerable to severe damage about coastal areas of Burrum Heads. Doppler radar indicated the presence of a strong" mesocyclone just offshore of Burrum Heads prior to impact. Rapid Damage Assessment data supplied by Queensland Fire and Emergency Services showed a clear path of damage through Burrum Heads and included notes about 14 properties with at least "Severe" damage. NULL"

It was concluded that damage in parts of Dundowran Beach matched the specifications of an F1 tornado. The evidence used to come to this conclusion included an image of some snapped and/or uprooted trees at a property at Dundowran Beach. Given the strength of the mesocyclone and the size of the trees uprooted in the image it is possible that there may have been some F2 or greater damage in the area. However, as there was no Rapid Damage Assessment conducted by Queensland Fire and Emergency Services and no detailed media report attached to the image it was decided that there was insufficient evidence to commit to a stronger damage specification. The sixth confirmed tornado during the TC Oswald tornado event. Doppler radar indicated the presence of a strong" mesocyclone over the area at the time and in fact it appeared to be one of the stronger mesocyclones evident on radar during the entire event. No Rapid Damage Assessment was conducted by Queensland Fire and Emergency Services in the area after the event

Media images showed a large storage shed blown over at Bony Mountain and a decimated, near-completed" home at Pratten. Media articles wrote of 6 houses with lost roofs
